      "question": "The product of a non-zero rational and an irrational number is always:",
      "answer": "(B)",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Consider a rational $r \\neq 0$ and irrational $i$.",
          "If $ri$ were rational, then $i$ would be the ratio of two rationals, which is rational, a contradiction."
        ],
        "derivation": "\\text{Let } r = \\frac{p}{q}, i \\text{ be irrational. } r \\times i = k \\Rightarrow i = \\frac{kq}{p} \\Rightarrow i \\text{ is rational, contradiction.}"
      },
      "topic": "Real Numbers",
      "subtopic": "Irrational Numbers",
      "marks": 1,
      "type": "mcq",
      "difficulty": "simple",
